<br>
for example, the following:<br>
Ç´Ç¡ÇƒÇ≠ÇæÇ≥Ç¢<br>
is romanized &quot;kitte kudasai&quot;, and the double t's indicate that the sound is pronounced as mentioned above, as opposed to &quot;kite kudasai&quot;:<br>
Ç´ÇƒÇ≠ÇæÇ≥Ç¢<br>
<br>
the difference is not trivial.  in the first case you are asking someone to cut something (from &quot;kiru&quot; - &quot;to cut&quot;) and in the second you are asking them to come to you (from &quot;kuru&quot; - &quot;to come&quot; (don't worry if the conjugation on this one seems screwed up, it's a special case verb)).  the 'small tsu' consanant doubling is an essential part of conjugating japanese words.<br>
<br>
